==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fardi-'', from Indo-European ''*per-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[ferd]] (Frisian [[feard]]), Old Saxon [[fard]] (Dutch [[vaart]]), Old High German [[fart]] (German [[Fahrt]]), Old Norse [[ferð]] (Swedish [[färd]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πορθμος]] ‘crossing’, Latin [[portus]] ‘refuge, port’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /fyɹd/

===Noun===
'''fyrd''' ''f''
# a country's [[army]], the entire land force of a country or nation
# military service
# a specific [[army]] or [[expedition]]

